g.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [2,1,3,2,1]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation:\nOne of the optimal solutions is to remove nums[0], nums[2] and nums[3].\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [1,3,2,1,3,3]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation:\nOne of the optimal solutions is to remove nums[1] and nums[2].\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [2,2,2,2,3,3]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation:\nnums is already non-decreasing.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 100\n1 <= nums[i] <= 3\n\n \nFollow-up: Can you come up with an algorithm that runs in O(n) time complexity?\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve the problem of finding the minimum number of operations to make the array `nums` non-decreasing, we can use dynamic programming. The idea is to maintain a count of the minimum operations needed to make the array non-decreasing up to each point, considering the possible values (1, 2, or 3) at each position.\n\nHere's the step-by-step plan:\n1. We will use a dynamic programming array `dp` where `dp[i]` represents the minimum number of operations needed to make the array non-decreasing up to the `i-th` element.\n2. We initialize `dp` with three elements, each representing the minimum operations needed to make the array non-decreasing if the last element of the array is 1, 2, or 3 respectively.\n3. We iterate through the array and update the `dp` array based on the current element.\n4. The final answer will be the minimum value in the `dp` array after processing all elements.\n\nLet's implement this approach in Python:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Initialize dp array with large numbers\n        dp = [0, 0, 0]\n        \n        for num in nums:\n            # Update dp for each possible last element in the non-decreasing sequence\n            new_dp = [0] * 3\n            new_dp[0] = dp[0] + (num != 1)\n            new_dp[1] = min(dp[0], dp[1]) + (num != 2)\n            new_dp[2] = min(dp[0], dp[1], dp[2]) + (num != 3)\n            dp = new_dp\n        \n        # The result is the minimum value in the dp array\n        return min(dp)\n\n# Example usage:\n# sol = Solution()\n# print(sol.minimumOperations([2,1,3,2,1]))  # Output: 3\n# print(sol.minimumOperations([1,3,2,1,3,3]))  # Output: 2\n# print(sol.minimumOperations([2,2,2,2,3,3]))  # Output: 0\n```\n\nThis solution runs in O(n) time complexity, where n is the length of the array `nums`, because we iterate through the array once and perform constant-time updates for each element. The space complexity is O(1) since the `dp` array has a fixed size of 3.", "estimated_date": 1691884800000}